  <div slot="timeline">
    <Timeline>
      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 1: Deciding on my Topic" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image1.jpg" 
        description="A cool fireworks photo from Yu Kodama, Getty Images.">
        <p>My thought process for this project was simply that at the time, I thought fireworks were fascinating (I still do) because they look really cool. The chemistry behind them is well studied, and would be publicly available. I just needed to learn how they work, what is inside them, and how to get rid of these components... simple, right?</p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 2: Creating Firework Schematic" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image2.jpg" 
        description="My sketch of a firework's internals.">
        <p>I first researched the parts of a firework. I drew this beautiful photo to explain my reasoning behind the components I used. </p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 3: Finding my Firework Recipes" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image3.jpg" 
        description="Sketch website I found all of my recipes on: <a href='https://pyrodata.com/PyroGuide/index.php%5Etitle=Category_Compositions.htm'>PyroData</a>"
        <p>Funny thing about finding super specific recipes for fireworks: it's not easy. My first attempt (asking ChatGPT) resulted in it telling me it can't help me with dangerous activities. Nonetheless, I went to a forum and found this SUPER specific website with tons of information (linked in image description). I even read the website casually for a bit.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 4: Deciding Which Fireworks to Make and Aggregating Recipes" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image4.jpg" 
        description="The recipes for the 'stars' (the cool flashy parts of fireworks) and which colours I chose.">
        <p>This is definitely where I sent myself down the path of pain. I chose to do 5 different colours and made assumptions, like that I would produce 1000 fireworks a day, 200 of each colour... I was foolish.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 5: Tabulate All of the Molecules" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image5.jpg" 
        description="I can't fit all of this in a nice screenshot, download the report if you want to see the whole table.">
        <p>There were a LOT of components.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 6: Make Assumptions" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image6.jpg" 
        description="There were 8 assumptions total.">
        <p>The assumptions started simple and evolved as I worked on the project, because I would often encounter something that was unreasonable for me to do without the assumptions.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 7: Decide Steps and Design Reactor" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image7.jpg" 
        description="A super elaborate reactor made in DWSIM. This obviously didn't work, but it was just to show what the layout was like.">
        <p>Went piece by piece through each group of molecules and came up with splits, flocculation steps, treatments, etc. Used DWSIM to make the whole layout even though it would have been nearly impossible to get it to function properly.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

          <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 8: Run Numbers, Apply Assumptions, Calculate Status at Each Step" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image8.jpg" 
        description="Part of the assignment was making tables for every individual process, so this is how I formatted them.">
        <p>My project was built basically on assumptions like that certain steps would remove 95% of their target compound, though these assumptions were primarily based on actual papers or product descriptions. Mass balance calculations had to be run on each process, which was just adding numbers in a spreadsheet. I used ChatGPT for everything after the first 3.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

      <TimelineItem 
        date="Step 9: Wrap up and Submit" 
        imageSrc="/images/projects/fireworks/firework_image9.jpg" 
        description="How I ended my paper.">
        <p>That was basically the entire creative process of designing of the firework treatment plant. I left out the parts where I would actually perform mass balance and find out that 3 steps ago I lost chlorine atoms, or that my concentration is way above the environmentally friendly limit. There is a reason it took 27 hours.</p>
      </TimelineItem>

    </Timeline>
